\code{model_table()} creates a \code{mdl_tbl} object — the notebook of models. It
collects \code{mdl} vectors (fitted models from \code{\link[=fit]{fit()}} with \code{raw = FALSE}),
\code{fmls} objects (formulas not yet fit), and other \code{mdl_tbl} objects into a
single data frame where each row is one model: its formula, its causal
roles, its fitting context (data, strata, subsets), and its results.
\code{mdl_tbl()} is a documented alias; the class itself is named \code{mdl_tbl}.

The table is the working surface of an analysis. Its print method
summarizes what has been fit, what failed, and what is still waiting;
\code{\link[=summary]{summary()}} maps the fleet; \code{\link[=flatten_models]{flatten_models()}} pulls out estimates;
\code{\link[=model_failures]{model_failures()}} explains failures. See \link{model_table_helpers} for the
